<HEADLINE>
FT  25 SEP 93 / Labour tax reform 'could raise Pounds 8bn'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday unveiled proposals for a series of tax reforms that it said
could raise Pounds 8bn over two years without increasing the basic rate of
income tax.
The party also claimed families were facing an extra tax bill of nearly
Pounds 8 a week in national insurance contributions, excise duty and income
tax from next April. This was in addition to the higher fuel bills that
would result from the plan to impose value added tax on household fuel.
Labour labelled this the government's 'double whammy', in ironic reference
to the Conservatives' advertising slogan used against Labour in last year's
general election.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, said: 'Even the family on
three-quarters of average income is hit by the Tory double whammy.'
Among seven proposed tax reforms, Mr Brown said the government could save
Pounds 2bn over two years by ending the abuse of sovereign immunity whereby
companies traded 'under the umbrella of' national governments - as in the
case of the Kuwait Investment Office. He said at least a further Pounds 2bn
could be saved by ending the 'underpayment' of corporation tax.
He predicted water companies would pay 'next to no corporation tax right
throughout the decade' thanks to Pounds 7bn of tax allowances.
The Water Services Association, representing the 10 large water and sewerage
companies of England and Wales, said last night that 'water companies are
subject to the same tax rules as any other company'.
It said the companies can offset some investment against profits in tax
calculations. Because they are engaged in a large investment programme,
allowances have generally been greater than profits.
Mr Brown proposed saving another Pounds 1.25bn over two years by:
Preventing companies from paying dividends in shares instead of cash to
avoid paying advance corporation tax. Closing a loophole whereby capital
gains tax and inheritance tax 'interact', enabling some companies to claim
double tax relief.
Not implementing the foreign income dividend for holding companies proposed
by the government from November.
Further sums could be raised by retaining stamp duty on share transactions,
imposing a levy on 'excess' profits of privatised utilities, and
accelerating the shutdown of business expansion schemes.
</TEXT>
