<HEADLINE>
FT  25 SEP 93 / Hero's welcome as rival Nigeria leader flies in
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN, Africa Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHIEF Moshood Abiola, victor in Nigeria's annulled presidential elections in
June, yesterday flew back to Lagos to a hero's welcome.
He was met by a huge crowd of supporters who defied security arrangements
aimed at limiting the size of the reception.
Thousands of people, many dressed in the green and white colours of his
Social Democractic party, lined the roads and cheered the waving Chief
Abiola as he was driven the two miles to his home.
'All we are saying is give MKO a chance,' his supporters sang to the tune of
the popular John Lennon song, referring to Chief Abiola by his popular
nickname.
Chief Abiola, who has been abroad since August 3 seeking support after the
military annulled an election he believed he won, said he was ready for
dialogue to find a peaceful solution to the crisis.
'I am going to struggle with you for the materialisation of the mandate of
June 12 for the benefit of our nation and people,' he told supporters.
The annulment of the June election plunged Nigeria into its worst crisis
since the 1967-70 civil war and still threatens the unity of Africa's most
populous nation.
While Chief Abiola was abroad the military government handed over power to
an unelected interim government.
Speaking at his Lagos headquarters, he said that during his travels he
received appeals from many Nigerians to ensure peace and the unity and
stability of Nigeria.
'Now that I am back. . . I am ready and willing to talk to anyone and
encourage any discussion with any group of people as long as such discussion
will take place on the basis of justice, fair play and the people's will as
expressed on June 12,' he said.
'It is a statement of political fact that all problems can be resolved
through dialogue. Indeed, even wars are finally resolved around the
conference table,' Mr Abiola said.
Chief Ernest Shonekan, head of the interim government, has said his
administration was prepared to talk with Mr Abiola to end the political
impasse.
Despite his warm welcome in Lagos, the heart of his political stronghold,
many of Mr Abiola's supporters fear he has missed the boat. A general strike
failed to shift the new military-led government from its plans to hold fresh
elections next March.
Many of Mr Abiola's supporters have also been disappointed by his extended
absence, which began when he fled Lagos in his private jet, fearing for his
life. He nevertheless has the capacity to revive protest in the south, where
his support is considerable.
</TEXT>
